species_comments: Continuing, originally found by Albert Linkowski. It was initially spotted today by Kevin, but it was so distant out to the East and such a brief look he couldn't positively ID looking in his bins. I later got a few decent looks through my scope. It was flying very low, often disappearing from sight, but there was also a female harrier in the area, which was both distracting and provided a useful comparison. The owl had slightly shorter and broader wings, somewhat deeper wingbeats, and an all dark dorsal side with no white rump. Although it was difficult to see very well, I got the overall impression that the owls body structure was stockier. When gliding, the owl would bank a little harder or longer than the harrier on average and was generally less teetering.
Seems like I'm starting to make it an annual tradition to find an absurdly distant Merlin and still try to get digiscope photos of it 😅 I checked Google Earth, and this was over a quarter mile away.
Singing! I don't think I've ever heard their song before.
observed male bring prey to nest area. Female rose from ground and male passed prey to female in mid-air.--Female returned to ground (nest hidden in reeds?) and male continued patrol
Light morph adult flying south. Not super uncommon in the area, but first record at this location.

species_comments: Two birds seen together in the main pond during low tide (the water level was so low that even the LESA could foraging at almost the entire area. I did not see these two at first, but shortly before sunset they flew with a group of Greater Yellowlegs from the central part of  marsh (an area that is not visible to an observer, but undoubtedly has a good habitat for shorebirds etc.) to the open area of the main pond.----Hotspot first record.This is  also the 6th record for Suisun Bay, four of which are from Waterbird Regional Preserve (part of Mococo wetlands). All these records  are apparently from Contra Costa County, surprisingly no records from the northern part of the bay (Suisun County) yet.----Distant, low quality photos taken in low light.

Same bird reported the last few days at Nichols Rd seen on and all around the main pond putting on a great show with several short fairly close flights and eventually flying over to Shell Pond. It's impossible to see Shell Pond from here, but I followed it in flight and it definitely seemed to be descending in the right area to land there.

We continued to the pond area and found the Sabine's Gull in the pond. It flew around several times giving a nice view of the distinctive wing pattern with white triangle. species_comments: Lifer! Continuing juveniles found last week by Albert. Medium-sized Calidris sandpipers that are much larger compared to the many Least Sandpipers there with bulkier bodies, longer necks, and slightly longer bills and legs. Sadly, I only got a brief look before they were flying off together to the northwest. It's possible they didn't go super far because I lost them before they would have reached the harbor. Their flight calls were notably lower-pitched and more distinctly trilled than those of the peeps. I think Least Sandpiper flight calls are also trilled, but sometimes it's so fast you can't really tell. Hanging around the flock here for another half hour there were never any similarly (relatively) low-pitched calls.----Two and a half years ago, when all the pandemic-related lock-downs were relatively brand new, I started birding my neighborhood extensively. As I did, I started finding birds that hadn't been reported in the area before - not rare ones, just fairly common things that no one had put on eBird in Bay Point because of how little anyone else ever birds here. I was still very much a novice at the time, but I started suggesting locations as hotspots and hoping if I saw enough birds it would attract more people to bird here, and then who knows what would be found! I can't really claim it has anything to do with me, but this fall, that dream of other people birding and finding cool things in my hometown has absolutely come to pass. Pectoral Sandpipers are great, and I was thrilled to see them, but they're far from the only unusual finds to turn up in the past few weeks. While not really rare in a lot of areas, Chipping Sparrow and Willow Flycatcher are both firsts for 94565 and beyond, and then there's the really good stuff: Baird's Sandpiper, Sabine's Gull, and (are you kidding me?!) Red-throated Pipit! I didn't get to see half of these birds, but just knowing they're here, practically in my back yard, is a really cool feeling. Of course, there's one thing these birds all have in common: they were all initially spotted by none other than Albert Linkowski. If I were to tabulate the finders of all the rare birds I've ever chased in the county, I'd probably see his name on a huge percentage of them. I appreciate him sharing these great sightings, enabling others including myself to enjoy these short-time visitors, but also thanks just for birding Bay Point. We always need to be selective about where and how we spend our time, and it means a lot to me that he's chosen to use some of his here in this often passed-over location.
